message.content:
Unfortunately, it's impossible to accurately reverse-engineer a Solidity source code from an Ethereum bytecode. The bytecode is a compiled version of the Solidity source code that the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) can interpret and execute. The compilation process is one-way, meaning it's not feasible to generate the original Solidity source code from the compiled bytecode. 

While it's technically possible to decompile the bytecode into a more human-readable assembly, this still wouldn't provide you with the original Solidity code. The resultant assembly code would be much more difficult to understand and work with than Solidity code. 

Therefore, it's always a good practice to keep a copy of your original Solidity source code. For open-source projects, the source code is typically made available on platforms like Github for others to review and use under the specified license terms.
